          "body": "The eschatological pivot at verse 11 is the most structurally significant verse in the entire book of Amos. After eight and a half chapters of covenant lawsuit, divine pursuit, and judgment doxology, God speaks a promise He introduces with a time-marker — 'In that day' — and then supplies four first-person verbs: I will raise up, wall up, raise up again, rebuild. The subject is 'the fallen booth of David.' The choice of *sukkah* (booth, temporary shelter) rather than *bayit* (house) or *hekal* (palace/temple) is deliberately humble: by Amos's time the Davidic dynasty ruled only Judah, a minor player; by the time of the exile it would be utterly fallen. God's promise does not wait for the dynasty to reconstitute itself — He promises to raise it when it is at its lowest. The purpose of the restoration is stated in verse 12: that the restored community may possess the remnant of Edom and all the nations called by God's name. This is the chapter's most startling expansion — former enemies (Edom) and all the nations bearing God's name are incorporated under the restored Davidic order. James at the Jerusalem Council in Acts 15:16-17 cites this passage directly from the Septuagint to argue that Gentile inclusion in the church was not a novelty but the fulfillment of what Amos already announced. The fallen booth of David, in the apostolic interpretation, finds its ultimate raising-up in the resurrection and exaltation of Jesus Christ, the Son of David."
